# DR Troubleshooting Pipeline — Audit Logging

## Overview

This document describes the per-session CSV audit logging implementation in
`dr_troubleshooting_pipeline.py`. It is written as an implementation guide
so that an agent can replicate this pattern in any Open WebUI Pipeline.

---

## Requirements

- Every user prompt and LLM response from a troubleshooting session must be
  captured to a CSV file for audit purposes.
- Onboarding exchanges (module selection, part number selection) must NOT be
  logged — only actual troubleshooting Q&A turns.
- Each chat session must produce its own separate CSV file.
- The log file must never crash or interrupt the pipeline if a write fails.

---

## Dependencies Added

The following standard library imports are required. Add them to the top of
the pipeline file alongside existing imports:

```python
import csv
from datetime import datetime, timezone
from pathlib import Path
```

No third-party packages are needed beyond what the pipeline already uses.

---

## Valve Added

Add `LOG_FILE_PATH` to the `Valves` inner class inside `Pipeline`. This
allows the admin to configure the log directory from the Open WebUI UI:

```python
class Valves(BaseModel):
    # ... existing valves ...
    LOG_FILE_PATH: str = "./dr_chat_logs/dr_chat_log.csv"
```

The parent directory of this path is used as the log directory. The filename
portion is used as a naming template prefix only — actual filenames are
generated per session (see below). The directory is created automatically on
first write if it does not exist.

---

## Instance Variables Added

Add the following to `__init__`:

```python
# Maps chat_id -> session start timestamp string
# Ensures all turns in one chat go to the same file
self._session_starts: dict[str, str] = {}
```

This can also be initialised lazily inside `outlet()` using `hasattr` if
preferred (see outlet implementation below).

